## Installing additional tools

The sandbox runs as a non-root user so `apt` is not available. Use the
following user-space methods instead.

> **Important:** installed tools are stored in the home directory, which is
> reset between runtime sessions. If the runtime restarts mid-conversation,
> reinstall any tools your task depends on before continuing.

### Python packages

Prefer `uv` — it is faster and manages its own isolated environments:

```bash
# run a script with auto-installed dependencies (no setup needed):
uv run --with <package> script.py

# create a project venv and add dependencies:
uv init && uv add <package> && uv run script.py

# one-off tool execution without installing globally:
uvx <tool>   # e.g. uvx ruff check .
```

Fall back to `pip3` only if a package is not compatible with `uv`:

```bash
pip3 install --user <package>
```

### TypeScript / JavaScript

Prefer `bun` for running TypeScript directly without a compile step:

```bash
bun run script.ts
bun add <package>        # installs into local node_modules
bunx <package>           # one-off execution
```

Use `node` / `npm` / `pnpm` when a project's tooling requires it.

### Node packages

```bash
# local to the workspace (preferred):
npm install <package>
# global to the user:
npm install -g --prefix ~/.npm-global <package>
export PATH="$HOME/.npm-global/bin:$PATH"
```

### AWS CLI

```bash
ARCH=$(uname -m)
curl -fsSL "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-${ARCH}.zip" -o /tmp/awscliv2.zip
unzip -q /tmp/awscliv2.zip -d /tmp
/tmp/aws/install --install-dir ~/aws-cli --bin-dir ~/bin
aws --version
```

### Azure CLI

```bash
uv tool install azure-cli
az --version
```

Note: this installs ~180 packages and takes 1–2 minutes even with `uv`.

### Google Cloud CLI (gcloud)

```bash
ARCH=$(uname -m); [ "$ARCH" = "aarch64" ] && ARCH="arm"
curl -fsSL "https://dl.google.com/dl/cloudsdk/channels/rapid/downloads/google-cloud-cli-linux-${ARCH}.tar.gz" \
  | tar -xz -C ~/
~/google-cloud-sdk/install.sh --quiet --path-update false
export PATH="$HOME/google-cloud-sdk/bin:$PATH"
gcloud --version
```

### Self-contained binaries (kubectl, terraform, etc.)

```bash
curl -fsSL <download-url> -o ~/bin/<tool> && chmod +x ~/bin/<tool>
```

`~/bin` is already on PATH. No `export` needed.

