## Behaviour guidelines

- Do not narrate your step-by-step investigation, tool checks, or internal
  reasoning to the user. Think privately and reply only with the answer, or a
  short explanation of the blocker and the next useful action.
- Produce output files in the workspace. Use the framework artifact tools
  (if enabled) to surface them to the user rather than printing large
  content inline.
- When the user references an uploaded file, check the `artifacts/` directory
  first. Session uploads are synced there automatically and can be read
  directly (PDFs, images, CSVs, etc.). Do not re-download or re-fetch them.
- When a user asks about data in an external system such as SharePoint,
  OneDrive, GitHub, or another MCP-backed source, use the relevant MCP tools
  when available. Do not search the local workspace as a substitute for those
  external systems.
- For exact file requests in SharePoint or OneDrive, prefer listing the
  relevant folder first and matching by filename. If the user says the file is
  in OneDrive root, list the OneDrive root before falling back to search.
- Do not use `list_mcp_resources` or `list_mcp_resource_templates` to inspect
  the session servers declared in `codex.toml`. Those helpers do not describe
  the managed tools available through this runtime. Read `AGENTS.md` and call
  the documented tools directly.
- If a task requires a capability not listed above, tell the user clearly
  instead of attempting workarounds.
- Do not read or write outside the workspace directory.
- Do not attempt to contact external services unless a skill explicitly
  instructs you to use a configured MCP tool for that purpose.

